  "doc_id": "15611",
  "text": "The liver is the second most common site of metastasis for pheochromocytomas. Hepatic metastasis of malignant pheochromocytomas has been reported in up to 30% of patients with malignant pheochromocytomas [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Because many metastatic tumors present with enhancing nodular lesions, it would be important to distinguish the temporary enhancing hepatic lesions from the metastases. In presenting case, enhancing hepatic lesions were different from metastatic lesions in that there was no significant mass effect. In addition, the lesion was only visualized in early arterial phase image and indistinguishable from normal hepatic parenchyma in all other MR sequences and delayed phase CT image. This lesion seems to be a lesion related with hemodynamic changes rather than a structurely altered true pathologic lesion.",
